<br>
The Bible makes it clear - believe with your heart that God raised Jesus from the dead and confess with your mouth that Jesus is Lord - then you will be saved.  Works are not a part of salvation, they were in the Old Testament Law, but not in the New Covenant of Christ.  Now if your works don't reflect Christ after you've believed with your heart and confessed with your mouth, then there hasn't been any growth or maturity and there's the risk that the seed did not fall on good soil.<br>
<br>
That's looking at the parable of the sower and the seeds that fell on the path, the weeds, the good soil and all that.  The seeds are God's salvation offered freely through Christ.  If the salvation lands on good soil, it takes root.  The person is saved and they start growing and as they grow, the good works begin to show - which are things like forgiving others and showing mercy and all that.  But without salvation being there first, the good works we might do are not directly related to Christ.  The implications of the verses in which you have provided are all in reference to those who have already accepted the free gift of salvation.<br>
<br>
Now you seem to imply that my salvation (as is everyone's salvation) is completely based on our ability to be good people and act according to God's will.<br>
<br>
I don't know about you, but I'm not perfect.  I don't always say the right thing.  I'm not always self-less.  My thoughts are not always pure and holy.  I can sometimes hold grudges and be unforgiving.  From what you're saying, if my co-worker tonight offended me and I didn't automatically forgive them but started thinking of how I could get revenge, I would lose my salvation.  That's how you are sounding to me - that my salvation is completely dependent on my actions.  And it's not enough for me to simply avoid sin, but I have to actually do things to keep or earn my salvation.  As if I can't receive God's forgiveness until I forgive others.  That is backwards from what the Bible says.  Jesus said, &quot;Forgive others as I have forgiven you.&quot;  Jesus forgave me first, before I ever forgave anyone else.  I can not forgive until I've first been forgiven.  I can not show love until I have first been shown love.<br>
<br>
I love because He first loved me.  I forgive because He first forgave me.  I show mercy because He first showed mercy on me.  That's what the Bible says.  Our actions as Christians come as a result of first being shown what we then show others.  I can't forgive others in the context that God wants me to until I first experience His forgiveness and I can't earn it.  Do you see what I'm saying?<br>
<br>
Let's say you wrong me.  You beat me up and stole my car.  How can I know how to forgive you unless I have experienced that forgiveness first?  Lost people can forgive others because they've experienced some kind of forgiveness.  Perhaps they had forgiving parents.  So they show the kind of forgiveness they have been shown.  But unless you know Jesus and have experienced His salvation which you can not experience without knowing Him through what the Bible tells us, it's not the same kind of forgiveness. <br>
<br>
The Bible is clear, good actions can't save us.  Only Jesus can and He will not impose His grace on us if we don't want it.  So those who have never heard of Him, He doesn't impose His grace on because they haven't wanted it.  They haven't heard, but He's not going to force Himself upon them.  Now I believe we all are given the opportunity to be saved, no one will go to hell who did not choose that path.<br>
<br>
My salvation is not dependent on my ability to forgive and show mercy.  If that's so, I lost my salvation a long time ago because it was years after I became a Christian before I really started to understand that, I held a lot of grudges against people while I was a Christian.  But I know was saved during that because once Jesus gets you, He doesn't just let go.<br>
<br>
God calls Himself our Father, we are His children.  The Bible says He disciplines His children.  Parents only discipline their children when they misbehave, when they break the rules.  So when we, His children who have been saved by grace, are unforgiving and unmerciful, He doesn't disown us, He disciplines us to teach us a lesson and to teach us to start showing it.  It comes after salvation and our salvation is not dependent upon it.  Now if we don't learn from God and we harden our hearts against Him, then I would say the seed never fell on good soil and either you never really accepted His salvation or you lost salvation (though some believe you can't lose it).  But even those of us of good soil - we're still not perfect.<br>
<br>
Salvation is not earned, the Bible is clear on that.  You have to accept it freely. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
